The marketing literature notes the importance of relational benefits (

ben

) in maintaining satisfying relationships (cf. Gwinner, Gremler, and Bitner 1998; Reynolds and Beatty 1999), with benefits serving as a driving force for maintaining relationships (Reynolds and Beatty 1999). Gwinner, Gremler, and Bitner’s widely accepted paradigm includes special treatment, social, and confidence benefits. Special treatment benefits refer to the preferential treatment customers may obtain from an ongoing relationship with a provider. Social benefits refer to the personal bonds and friendships between the customer and members of the firm. Finally, confidence benefits relate to the comfort or security a consumer has in a relationship and are similar to trust (Hennig-Thurau, Gwinner and Gremler 2002).

As noted earlier, we identify two important switching barriers: sunk costs and procedural switching costs. Sunk costs (

sunk

) are similar to relationship or past investments (Bendapudi and Berry 1997; Meyer et al. 2002). While we believe that sunk costs should positively link to all three commitments, only the relationship between sunk costs and calculative commitment is established in the literature (see Table 1 for relevant studies). However, when one invests time, money and/or effort in a relationship, one should feel more positively toward the service provider and desire to stay (i.e., affective commitment). This may be due to escalation of commitment (Bobocel and Meyer 1994). Further, Bendapudi and Berry (1997, p. 20) address escalating commitment as self-justification, “They may rationalize that their commitment is not driven by dependence but instead by their own volition, for instance, by dedication.”
